    {
      "id": "user-1774463309116",
      "createdAt": "2026-03-25T18:28:29.116Z",
      "role": "user",
      "content": "what can you tell me about the VPD vapor pressure deficit",
      "source": "text"
    },
    {
      "id": "assistant-1774463309116",
      "createdAt": "2026-03-25T18:28:30.827Z",
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "VPD, or Vapor Pressure Deficit, is the difference between the amount of moisture in the air and how much moisture the air can hold when it's saturated. It's a crucial metric for plant growth because it influences transpiration rates. A high VPD means the air is dry and the plant will transpire more, which can be good for nutrient uptake but can also lead to stress if too high. A low VPD means the air is humid, reducing transpiration and potentially leading to issues like mold or nutrient lockout. Maintaining an optimal VPD range is key for healthy plant development.",
      "source": "text",
      "meta": {
        "model": "grok-4-1-fast / gemini-2.5-flash"
      }
    },
    {
